mbing within the city's postwar urban identity in unique ways, informing the discourse of reconstruction as well as its physical manifestations in the city's revival. Diehl's analysis reveals how these atomic narratives shaped both the way Nagasaki rebuilt and the ways in which popular discourse on the atomic bombings framed the city's experience for decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAtomic bomb victimszJapanzNagasaki-shi. 0aCity planningzJapanzNagasaki-shixHistoryy20th century. 0aCollective memoryzJapanzNagasaki-shi. 0aReconstruction (1939-1951)zJapanzNagasaki-shi. 4aAsian Studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aWorld War II. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  athe aftermath of Nagasaki, Hiroshima, atomic bombs, disaster recovery, nuclear attacks, atomic bomb survivors.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170943240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709432/original  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-064982-6  